      bio: `Immanuel Kant spent nearly his entire life in the provincial Prussian city of Königsberg (now Kaliningrad, Russia), yet he produced a body of work that redirected the entire course of Western philosophy. His three Critiques — of Pure Reason, Practical Reason, and Judgment — represent one of the most ambitious attempts ever made to establish the foundations, limits, and legitimate scope of human knowledge and value.

Kant described himself as awakened from "dogmatic slumber" by reading Hume, whose radical skepticism about causation seemed to undermine the possibility of scientific knowledge. Kant's response was the "Copernican Revolution" of his Critique of Pure Reason: just as Copernicus solved astronomical puzzles by moving the observer rather than the stars, Kant proposed that the mind does not passively receive experience but actively structures it. Space, time, and causality are not features of things as they are in themselves; they are forms that the human mind imposes on experience.

This led to Kant's famous distinction between phenomena (things as they appear to us, structured by our cognitive faculties) and noumena (things as they are in themselves, forever beyond our knowledge). We can know the empirical world rigorously, but we cannot have theoretical knowledge of God, the soul, or freedom — these lie beyond possible experience.

In ethics, Kant argued that morality must be grounded in reason alone, not in consequences or feelings. His Categorical Imperative — "Act only according to that maxim whereby you can at the same time will that it should become a universal law" — provides a formal principle for determining right action. A second formulation commands us to treat humanity, whether in ourselves or others, always as an end and never merely as a means.`
