      bio: `Albert Einstein is perhaps the only scientist whose name has become synonymous with genius in popular culture — and this popular perception, for once, is not far wrong. His intellectual achievements in the first decades of the twentieth century were without historical precedent: in 1905 alone, a year he later called his "annus mirabilis," he published four papers that each transformed a different area of physics.

The paper on the photoelectric effect — for which he received the Nobel Prize in 1921 — introduced the photon and helped establish quantum theory. The papers on Brownian motion and special relativity each inaugurated major research programs. And the paper on mass-energy equivalence gave the world E=mc².

Special relativity, published when Einstein was 26 and working as a patent clerk, began with two postulates: that the laws of physics are the same in all inertial reference frames, and that the speed of light in vacuum is constant for all observers. From these two simple principles, Einstein derived consequences that upended classical physics: time dilation, length contraction, the relativity of simultaneity, and mass-energy equivalence.

General relativity, completed a decade later in 1915, was an even more audacious achievement. It replaced Newton's theory of gravitation with a geometric description: mass curves spacetime, and what we perceive as gravitational force is actually the motion of objects along the curved geometry of spacetime. This theory predicted the bending of light by gravity, the precession of Mercury's orbit, gravitational time dilation, and the existence of black holes and gravitational waves — all subsequently confirmed.

Despite his revolutionary contributions to quantum theory, Einstein never accepted the Copenhagen interpretation of quantum mechanics. His debates with Niels Bohr, conducted over decades, remain the most important extended philosophical argument in the history of science.`
