      bio: `David Chalmers has had the unusual experience of coining a term — "the hard problem of consciousness" — that immediately entered the vocabulary of an entire field and permanently shaped its self-understanding. Since his landmark 1995 paper and subsequent book The Conscious Mind, Chalmers has been the central figure in the philosophy of mind, defining the problem space that others work within or against.

Chalmers was born in Australia and trained first in mathematics before turning to philosophy and cognitive science. He completed his PhD at Indiana University under Douglas Hofstadter, author of Gödel, Escher, Bach. He has held positions at the University of Arizona and New York University, where he is currently a professor of philosophy and co-director of the Center for Mind, Brain, and Consciousness.

The Hard Problem, as Chalmers formulated it, is the question of why there is subjective experience at all — why physical processes in the brain give rise to the felt quality of experience, rather than occurring "in the dark" without any inner dimension. He distinguished this from the "easy problems" of consciousness — explaining how the brain processes information, discriminates stimuli, and reports mental states — which, while scientifically difficult, are tractable by functional explanation. The Hard Problem, by contrast, resists any such explanation in principle.

Chalmers argued for this through thought experiments about "philosophical zombies" — conceivable creatures physically identical to humans but with no inner experience. If zombies are conceivable (which he argues they are), then consciousness is not logically entailed by any physical description, and physicalism as standardly construed is false.

More recently, Chalmers has engaged seriously with virtual reality and artificial intelligence, arguing in Reality+ that virtual worlds are genuine realities, not mere simulations, and exploring whether digital minds might be conscious.`
