      shortBio: 'Hume pushed empiricism to its radical limits, challenging causation, personal identity, and the rational basis of religion — and influencing virtually every philosopher who came after him.',
      ideas: ['Radical Empiricism', 'Bundle Theory of Self', 'Problem of Induction', 'Is-Ought Gap', 'Skepticism about Causation'],
      works: ['A Treatise of Human Nature', 'An Enquiry Concerning Human Understanding', 'Dialogues Concerning Natural Religion', 'An Enquiry Concerning the Principles of Morals'],
      bio: `David Hume is, by many accounts, the greatest philosopher ever to write in the English language — and one of the most dangerous. His radical empiricism systematically dismantled claims to knowledge that his predecessors had taken for granted: causation, personal identity, the external world, and the rational foundations of religious belief all fell under his skeptical scrutiny.

Hume was born in Edinburgh to a minor Scottish noble family. He attempted to remake philosophy as a Newtonian science of human nature — grounding all philosophical inquiry in careful observation of the human mind rather than a priori speculation. His masterwork, A Treatise of Human Nature, published when he was 28, was, as he ruefully noted, "dead born from the press." His later Enquiries brought his ideas to a wider audience with more accessible prose.

Hume's analysis of causation is his most consequential philosophical contribution. We perceive events succeeding one another; we do not perceive any necessary connection between them. When we say one event causes another, we are projecting a habit of association onto the world — not reporting a feature we observe. This analysis had devastating implications for scientific knowledge, which Hume recognized. Induction — reasoning from observed cases to general laws — rests on the assumption that the future will resemble the past. But we have no non-circular justification for this assumption. The problem of induction, as this came to be called, has never been definitively solved.

In ethics, Hume argued that moral judgments are expressions of sentiment, not rational discoveries. The famous is-ought gap — the observation that no "ought" follows logically from any "is" — has become one of the most discussed points in meta-ethics. And his critiques of natural theology, particularly in the posthumously published Dialogues Concerning Natural Religion, remain the most sophisticated philosophical challenges to arguments for the existence of God.`
